Take a close look at the glass test scene.
Those 9 clamps holding the armour glass were not tightly locked.
Some of those opened up after the ball was dropped, which possibly spread out the impact  by allowing the edges to deflect so the maximum curvature across the entire glass could become smaller.
The edges of the glass on the truck were tightly held by the surrounding metal and was more vulnerable to the same impact.
Elon should have not tried it.
I doubt it was planned.

Title: WATCH LIVE! Elon Musk presents the new Tesla Cybertruck Launch
Comment:
Got to admit, under the most dire circumstances, Elon Musk remains upbeat and focused to deliver. Even while presenting a new product that's damaged behind him.

He has a good point thou, "didn't go through". Toss that steel ball bearing at ANY truck window on the market right now and you'ld have a broken window.

I don't feel this test was really necessary, however, does add to safety. I was more impressed by the "dent test" to be honest. I love how they are making the truck heavier using Stainless Steel for the exoskeleton, than you have a heavy battery very low to the ground. Makes the truck VERY stable pulling, and they can get away with all this extra weight even if it weighs 9,000 lbs because they are using electric motors to power it!

Nothing but gobs of torque to get it moving, same as a locomotive. Still does 0-60 in 4 secs, not that I care about that, my truck probably does that in 10. I care about pulling a trailer on the highway and having my tow vehicle FIRMLY PLANTED. My truck should determine where that trailer goes, not the opposite.

Too funny, they have the glass on a rebound table and as they went to a higher level they loosened the retaining clamps to let it flex more at each drop. the last ball from the highest level made the glass panel bounce a couple inches.

The glass being in a fixed, solid frame in that poor excuse of a truck is what caused the thin laminate glass to shatter. Actual armored glass does not shatter like that though it is much thicker. A couple claw hammer blows and you could go right through that "armored" glass. What a joke.

What the absolute hell is that supposed to be?..... that‚Äôs terrible looking. Any one who actually uses a truck daily knows that this is not realistic. Try hauling feed, hay, fence post, manure, or tools in the back of this thing. Most of the time you're hauling all of that at once. Or getting a horse or livestock trailer through snow, mud or the twist and turns in the mountains. I‚Äôm a equine and live stock vet tech, I also spend my weekends riding. In this business you absolutely need a reliable truck or SUV. It's honestly mandatory. That's why I spent $40k on my SUV. Just looking at this I can tell you, you will not get far driving down to the pasture. It‚Äôs unrealistic for any type of working truck. So it‚Äôs far from comparable to the F150. Also, the reason aluminum is used on cars and not steel is because it absorbs the kinetic energy of the impact and is lighter - with steel the energy of the impact may end of going to the driver or the vehicle will go flying.

Elon: dear shareholders of tesla I present my next big and great, incredibly well thought out vehicle "the cybertruck"  

Shareholders (aka Elon): this is a marvelous idea it must be produced

Elon: (talks to himself on subway home from work) mutters incoherently) 

Shareholders: it must have cold rolled steel and we should say it shatter proof glass even though it's not and at the unveil you should have a team member throw a steel ball at the "claimed shatterproof glass" and then watch it shatter and to make yourself look like even more of a complete incompetent fucktard and to tarnish the tesla name just a little more have him throw the same ball at the rear window and watch it smash

Elon: hmm... (muttering incoherently) YESSSSSS it's a plan...



And we're back.. you see this vehicle if you can call it that is lacking everything it's got no real shape it's a brick with a couple of wheel arches and no mirrors... mirrors for fuck sake.. no in place cameras.. it's got no style it will not cope with real world conditions I'm assuming because it's tesla there's no actual 4x4 mode, where's the practicality? We know tesla loves to be unique but this is next level bullshit why did you have to stray from the standard design of a truck? Title: WATCH LIVE! Elon Musk presents the new Tesla Cybertruck Launch
Comment:
Whatever I may think about the appearance I can't see how this is supposed to move the transition to sustainable transportation needle. Elon's always made no bones about it not being for everyone but what's the point of it being so radically different that it seriously risks being a commercial flop, doing nothing truly meaningful, to contribute to Tesla's mission? 
As for functionality, overall Tesla has done an excellent job though the retractable rear cargo bay roof means nothing of any substantial height can be safely secured from would be sticky fingers & this is a major design flaw. I had hoped that it would've held a slightly broader mass market appeal but, upon seeing it for the first time, well, that sinking feeling in the pit of my stomach leading up to tonight's reveal, it's just gotten a hell of a lot worse. Can't see a single construction Co., farmer etc opting for this & as such this will in all likelihood remain something of a rich man's toy/diehard Tesla fans only. Even tonight's audience reactions seemed rather subdued when compared to ALL of the other Tesla reveal events.

Title: WATCH LIVE! Elon Musk presents the new Tesla Cybertruck Launch
Comment:
Hey everyone, notice there are no side view mirrors either. Everyone's missing the real implications of this design. It's designed for ultra low wind resistance. It's likely what allows the long range despite the extra weight. There are no mirrors and the steering wheel looks like a game controller. There is going to be heavy reliance on cameras and automated driving. 

Also, it will probably look better with a coat of paint.

Title: üî¥Tesla Truck Unveil Event LIVE REWINDüî¥
Comment:
I'd really like to see how this thing is put together, it would really give us an idea of how to improve the glass and panel issue you see demonstrated here.


Regarding the glass, soft supporting the window panels would have kept them from breaking, as shown by the comparative glass demonstration.  The regular car glas was held in place from the very start of the demonstration.  Normally the glass would shatter into tiny bits, which makes it possible to exit a vehicle if you are trapped in your vehicle after an accident.  The Telsa 'transparent metal-glass' (don't tell Scotty!) is held in place with the Destaco clamps at the lower drops.  At the higher drop they seem to be either reset or adjusted, watch how the glass jumps overcoming the clamping force of the toggle-clamps after the impact on the higher drop.  The impact of the highest drop is also at the center of the glass pane with a larger diameter ball.    


The hammer was a dead blow, soft hammer.  A ball peen hammer would have damaged the materials significantly as would a 5lb sledge hammer.  Now I am not easy on my truck, but would neither hit my vehicle with a hammer of any kind purposely... otherwise I would have dents.  As to the design, it's a truck so an ugly design does not bother me.  Having a rust free vehicle that can stand impacts is a plus on any day of the week.  Tesla can improve on the way panels are made with proper panel specific tooling.  It seems that the panels are cut via laser (maybe?) and formed individually on a press brake, it's hard to tell i haven't seen it in person.


Now if it lasts as long as my tundra, (2000 w/350k miles, nothing major fixed, same engine heads and drivetrain, 1 cracked windshield) it's a winner.

Comment:
Take a close look at the glass test scene.
Those 9 clamps holding the armour glass were not tightly locked.
Some of those opened up after the ball was dropped, which possibly spread out the impact  by allowing the edges to deflect so the maximum curvature across the entire glass could become smaller.
The edges of the glass on the truck were tightly held by the surrounding metal and was more vulnerable to the same impact.
Elon should have not tried it.
I doubt it was planned.

Title: üî¥Tesla Truck Unveil Event LIVE REWINDüî¥
Comment: The driving range is "between 400 and 500 miles." No more warming up the engine for fifteen minutes while breathing exhaust. No more chronic low-grade carbon monoxide toxicity. It has electric outlets for using power tools in remote places. A sledge hammer can't dent the steel. Zero to 60 mph in 2.9 seconds! Paylode: 2.75 tons (3,500 lbs). It tows 7 tons (14,000 lbs). The broken windows reflect an honest man's best efforts. I like that. Pricetags: $39,900, $49,900, $69,900. It's got a retro-futuristic look because it's made of rocket-grade steel that doesn't yield to delicate sculpting. Maybe it's not pretty enough for an image-conscious truck driver, but to me the beauty is in the quality steel, the clean air, and all the off-the-charts things it can do. I want one.

Title: üî¥Tesla Truck Unveil Event LIVE REWINDüî¥
Comment:
I HATED this at first. After all of the slick speculative renderings got my juices up, to see this childs drawing brought to life, just defied reality. Like many of you, I kept thinking, when is he going to let us in on the joke, and bring out the real truck. This was a bigger letdown after all the hype then the LOST finale and Phantom Menace rolled in to one.
But, little by little, I‚Äôm shocked to admit it‚Äôs growing on me. I think the possibilities afforded to them by the unibody design coupled with the super strong SS, created a monster. You can‚Äôt form cold rolled SS like you can mild steel. Ductility just isn‚Äôt there, hence the primitive forms. This reminds me of my gripe with Apple design, how refinement is measured by reduction of complexity, And less is more mindset.
However, for a truck, simplicity really is a virtue, and the severeness of simplicity here, actually makes a lot of sense. Hope it sells well enough to warrant v2. Guaranteed, it‚Äôll be far more easy on the eye.
Gotta hand it to Elon for having the balls to roll the dice on this radical of a design. He‚Äôs going to lose a lot of fans with this in the short term. Can‚Äôt wait to see how it develops.

Title: TESLA LIVE FULL HD - Cybertruck Unveil
Comment:
I actually mostly like the design. The weirdest feature is probably the kink where you'd expect a horizontal roof. This actually looks inefficient in terms of interior space, but presumably the ceiling height in the rear is sufficient anyway. The rest of the design is quite appealing in a sci-fi way.

I absolutely love the stainless steel construction which should make it last virtually forever. I've been thinking about this for car construction since not only is it really rugged and strong, it also means you don't need rust protection or paint which could save cost.

I wonder what gauge steel they're using though. Stainless steel is strong, but not so strong that it wouldn't dent from a sledgehammer if using normal car steel gauge.

The built-in bed cover and tail gate ramp are excellent practical features.

You have to credit Elon for having the balls to actually go through with this polarizing design.

Bottom line: I'm totally getting one of these.
